    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nTokyonight Moon is one of the most balanced night color schemes that gives Neovim or any editor a smooth look.\n\nThe Neovim default themes are too **primitive**, and I along with a lot of Neovim users demand Tokyonight-moon to be one of the built-in, modern LSP/Treesitter-backed themes.\n\n### Why is having an advanced, modern color scheme important?\n\nThe answer is simple:\nNeovim has a lot of default themes, but all of them **have some problems in certain UI areas.** This frustrates users into using external themes.\n\nMy suggestion is to remove all other less-tuned themes (keep the Catppuccin one) and add a single, well-tuned, modern standard theme  i.e., Tokyonight-moon.\n\nI know it is a challenge, but what if you exposed a simple theme configuration API that allows users to self-configure plugin highlight areas with the palettes of Tokyonight-moon?\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe expected behavior is to have a well-tuned Tokyonight-moon as a built-in theme that supports Treesitter, semantic tokens, and other highlight sectors. Additionally, users should be able to tune a plugin of their choice using the built-in theme's color palettes with ease.",
