            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Forgive my question, but is this issue AI assisted? The random bolded words and the tone suggests to me that it might be.\n\n> The Neovim default themes are too **primitive**, and I along with a lot of Neovim users demand Tokyonight-moon to be one of the built-in, modern LSP/Treesitter-backed themes.\n\nAll of the built-in color schemes come from Vim (besides `default`), so yes, they do not directly integrate with Nvim-only features.\n\n> My suggestion is to remove all other less-tuned themes (keep the Catppuccin one) and add a single, well-tuned, modern standard theme  i.e., Tokyonight-moon.\n\nWhy? The catppuccin theme also comes from Vim and also lacks the integrations you are describing.\n\n> I know it is a challenge, but what if you exposed a simple theme configuration API that allows users to self-configure plugin highlight areas with the palettes of Tokyonight-moon?\n\nUse `nvim_set_hl()`? I'm not exactly sure what you're asking for here.\n\n> The expected behavior is to have a well-tuned Tokyonight-moon as a built-in theme that supports Treesitter, semantic tokens, and other highlight sectors.\n\nI do think it would be cool to have Neovim modify Vim's upstream themes to support Nvim-only highlight groups. Not sure who would be maintaining that tho...",
